pragma language_version >= 0.16 && <= 0.23;

import CompactStandardLibrary;

// ============================================================================
// DARKVEIL + BONDING CURVE + ELIGIBILITY GATE PSM (merged) — Noctis Protocol
// ============================================================================
//
// This is the Tier C Midnight bonding curve — QUADRATIC pricing, NIGHT-
// denominated. Tier A never touches Midnight at all; its linear curve lives
// in a separate Aiken/Cardano contract (contracts/cardano/bonding_curve.ak).
// Tier B's public bonding curve ALSO moved to Cardano/Aiken (T24 resolution,
// 2026-07-09, see contracts/cardano/bonding_curve_tier_b.ak) — the public
// phase is public information by definition, so it never needed Midnight's
// privacy, and keeping it on Midnight would have needed a relayer bridge
// just so buyTokens could learn a Cardano ADA payment had happened, since
// ADA isn't representable as a Midnight-native unshielded token. Only
// Tier C keeps its public curve on Midnight, because Tier C's token and LP
// are Midnight-native too — there's no cross-chain payment problem for it
// to begin with.
//
// MERGED WITH eligibility_gate.compact (T25, 2026-07-10) AND darkveil.compact
// (T25 follow-up, 2026-07-10). The 5% cumulative wallet cap needs to be
// enforced against the SAME running total during DarkVeil registration,
// DarkVeil buy reveal (revealBuyCommit), AND this contract's own public
// buyTokens — all three need to read and write one shared
// `cumulativePurchases` map atomically. (At the time of this merge,
// registration-side enforcement lived in a standalone `checkAndUpdateCap`
// circuit; that circuit was later found to be dead code — nothing called
// it once revealBuyCommit/buyTokens enforced the cap inline — and removed
// entirely, the design requirement/T51. Registration itself doesn't touch this cap at all;
// only an actual purchase does.) Investigated whether Compact
// supports calling one deployed contract's circuit from another's — it does
// not: the compiler has stubbed-in external-contract-call syntax, but every
// call form tested fails with "contract types are not yet implemented"
// (verified against the installed compactc, not assumed). The one mechanism
// that DOES work, verified by compiling it, is folding `.compact` sources
// into one deployed contract with one shared ledger. So for Tier C,
// eligibility_gate's allowlist/registration/cap-tracking logic,
// darkveil's private commit/reveal buying logic, and bonding_curve's
// public-buy logic are now ONE PSM instead of three. Tier B still deploys
// eligibility_gate.compact AND darkveil.compact standalone (no bonding
// curve to merge with — that moved to Cardano) — the two tiers now use
// different shapes of "the eligibility gate" and "DarkVeil," which is an
// accepted consequence of this fix, not an oversight.
//
// T25's remaining gap (public-phase cap fixed, DarkVeil-phase purchases
// never counted) is CLOSED by this second merge — revealBuyCommit now
// updates cumulativePurchases the same way buyTokens does, using the same
// shared identity and the same walletCap.
//
// Also closes a related, previously-undiscovered gap: darkveil.compact had
// ZERO payment enforcement anywhere — revealBuyCommit verified the claimed
// price/allocation but never checked the buyer actually paid any NIGHT at
// all, for any tier. Fixed here for Tier C via receiveUnshielded, applied
// at REVEAL time specifically (not submit time) — this is deliberate, not
// an oversight: submitBuyCommit only stores a commitment hash, and the
// purchase amount is intentionally still hidden at that point (that's the
// whole privacy point of the commit/reveal pattern). Checking payment at
// submit time would require disclosing the amount to receiveUnshielded's
// argument, defeating that privacy property. Reveal time is when the
// amount is ALREADY meant to become public by design (see this file's
// PRIVACY ANALYSIS section), so enforcing payment there costs no
// additional disclosure beyond what the feature already does — reviewed
// against the privacy/selective-disclosure gold standard before landing,
// not after. Tier B's identical gap (also zero payment enforcement, any
// currency) is NOT fixed here — ADA can't be verified via receiveUnshielded
// the same way NIGHT can (same root cause as T24). Resolved separately as
// [T46] — Tier B's DarkVeil settlement (ADA payment + token delivery) moved
// to Cardano entirely (`ClaimDarkVeilTokens` on bonding_curve_tier_b.ak),
// since Compact can never custody ADA. This contract needed no change for
// that fix — it's Tier C only.
//
// Identity note: eligibility_gate.compact, bonding_curve.compact, and
// darkveil.compact previously derived the caller's UserPublicKey under
// THREE DIFFERENT domain-separated hashes ("noctis:user:pk:v1" /
// "noctis:curve:user:pk:v1" / "noctis:darkveil:user:pk:v1") — fine when
// they were separate contracts, but it would silently defeat the whole
// point of a shared cumulativePurchases map if kept: a buyer's DarkVeil
// identity, curve-phase identity, and eligibility identity would never
// match as the same map key. This merge standardizes on ONE identity
// derivation (eligibility_gate's original "noctis:user:pk:v1"/
// "noctis:governor:pk:v1" domains) for everything in this contract —
// balances, paidByBuyer, buyRecords, and now commitments/nullifiers too,
// are all keyed by that same identity, not the old per-file ones.
//
// Per CLAUDE.md's tier design, Tier A is deliberately the "weak" tier (weak
// per-address cap, simple linear pricing) and Tier B/C are deliberately
// "strong" (ZK-identity cap + a curve that accelerates faster the more of
// it one wallet buys). Do not flatten this to linear — that was tried in an
// earlier draft of this file and was a spec deviation, not a
// simplification. See internal tracking [T26] for the resolution history.
//
// Price formula: price = basePrice + k * sold^2
//   where k is chosen so that price = maxPrice at sold = curveSupply:
//   k = (maxPrice - basePrice) / curveSupply^2
//   i.e. price = basePrice + ((maxPrice - basePrice) * sold^2) / curveSupply^2
//
// Same k derivation — i.e. same curve SHAPE — as Tier B's Cardano-side
// curve (Jinx's explicit call: no per-tier steepness difference). basePrice/
// maxPrice/grossPayment are always in the smallest unit of NIGHT
// (micro-NIGHT).
//
// At sold=0:            price = basePrice
// At sold=curveSupply:  price = maxPrice
//
// No division in the circuit: division only appears in deriving k, which
// happens off-chain. Every on-chain check is a cross-multiplication
// (claimedPrice * curveSupply^2 == basePrice * curveSupply^2 + priceRange *
// sold^2) — same no-division pattern the original linear version used, just
// with sold^2/curveSupply^2 in place of sold/curveSupply. The bonding curve's
// total-raised *integral* (needed for graduation FDV / LP sizing planning)
// involves a cubic term with a /3 — that's an off-chain formal-verification
// and test-suite concern (CLAUDE.md's Security Audit Requirements), not
// something this circuit computes.
//
// Fee structure (2.0% total):
//   1.0% → creator escrow
//   0.6% → treasury
//   0.4% → ops wallet
//
// Graduation: when 100% of bonding curve tokens are sold, the launch
// "graduates" — LP is seeded and trading moves to the DEX.
//
// Reuses patterns from:
//   - midnight-expert FungibleToken (witness-derived identity, _update pattern)
//   - SilentLedger/ObfuscatedOrderbook (fill matching, order status)
//   - midnight-modules/access-control (governor pattern)
//   - midnight-modules/merkle-membership (allowlist gating)
//   - midnight-modules/commitment-nullifier (double-registration prevention)
//
// Compiler: compactc v0.31.1
// ============================================================================

// ============================================================================
// DATA STRUCTURES
// ============================================================================

export enum CurveState { Inactive, Active, Graduated, Cancelled }

export enum LaunchPhase { Pending, DarkVeil, Public, Graduated, Cancelled }

export struct UserSecretKey {
  bytes: Bytes<32>;
}

export struct UserPublicKey {
  bytes: Bytes<32>;
}

// Fee split configuration (in basis points: 100 = 1.0%)
struct FeeConfig {
  creatorBps: Uint<16>;   // 100 = 1.0%
  treasuryBps: Uint<16>;  // 60  = 0.6%
  opsBps: Uint<16>;       // 40  = 0.4%
  totalBps: Uint<16>;     // 200 = 2.0%
}

// Buy order record for tracking
struct BuyRecord {
  buyerKey: Bytes<32>;
  amount: Uint<128>;       // Token amount purchased
  pricePaid: Uint<128>;    // Total NIGHT paid (in microNIGHT)
  feeCharged: Uint<128>;   // Total fee extracted
  timestamp: Uint<64>;
}

// Input for buy record ID generation
struct BuyRecordIdInput {
  buyerKey: Bytes<32>;
  launchId: Bytes<32>;
  amount: Uint<128>;
  timestamp: Uint<64>;
}

// Input for computing a registration commitment from private data
// T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21, Medium): dropped the prover-chosen `nonce`
// field — same fix and reasoning as eligibility_gate.compact's parallel
// struct (this merged Tier C contract has its own copy of the same bug).
struct RegistrationCommitInput {
  userKey: Bytes<32>;
  launchId: Bytes<32>;
  bondAmount: Uint<128>;
}

// One level of a Merkle inclusion proof — the sibling hash at that level,
// and whether the node being folded up is the LEFT child (true) or RIGHT
// child (false) of the pair being hashed. T42 fix (2026-07-09).
struct MerkleProofEntry {
  sibling: Bytes<32>;
  goesLeft: Boolean;
}

// Input to a single Merkle tree node hash — domain-separated so this can
// never collide with any other persistentHash use in this contract even if
// the byte shape happened to match.
struct AllowlistNodeInput {
  domain: Bytes<32>;
  left: Bytes<32>;
  right: Bytes<32>;
}

// --- from darkveil.compact ---

// DarkVeil's own sub-phase within the overall LaunchPhase.DarkVeil period
// (registration vs buying vs closed) — a finer-grained state machine than
// LaunchPhase, tracked separately on purpose (same distinction the two
// separate source files had).
export enum DarkVeilState { Inactive, Registration, Buying, Closed, Cancelled }

export enum CommitStatus { Open, Revealed, Cancelled }

// Private buy commitment — hides the purchase amount and buyer identity
struct BuyCommit {
  commitment: Bytes<32>;    // Hash of (buyerKey, amount, price, nonce)
  nullifier: Bytes<32>;     // Unique per (buyerKey, launchId) — prevents double-buy
  timestamp: Uint<64>;      // When the commitment was placed
  status: CommitStatus;     // Open, Revealed, Cancelled
}

// Input for computing buy commitment from private data
struct BuyCommitInput {
  buyerKey: Bytes<32>;
  launchId: Bytes<32>;
  tokenAmount: Uint<128>;
  pricePerToken: Uint<128>;
  nonce: Bytes<32>;
}

// Input for computing nullifier (prevents double-buying)
// T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21, High): computeNullifier below (buyerKey +
// launchId, both public) is no longer used to GATE submitBuyCommit — see
// BuyNullifierInput/computeBuyNullifier and that circuit's own comment for
// why. Kept only as a standalone pure hash helper; nothing in this file
// calls it anymore.
struct NullifierInput {
  buyerKey: Bytes<32>;
  launchId: Bytes<32>;
}

// Input for computing the REAL buy nullifier (T-AUDIT fix, 2026-07-21).
struct BuyNullifierInput {
  domain: Bytes<32>;
  buyerSecret: Bytes<32>;
  launchId: Bytes<32>;
}

// ZK Fair Launch Certificate data
export struct FairLaunchCert {
  launchId: Bytes<32>;
  totalParticipants: Uint<64>;
  totalTokensAllocated: Uint<128>;
  totalRaised: Uint<128>;
  participationRate: Uint<8>;   // Percentage of allowlist that participated
  closeTimestamp: Uint<64>;
  certHash: Bytes<32>;          // Unique certificate hash
}

// Input for certificate hash computation
struct CertHashInput {
  launchId: Bytes<32>;
  totalParticipants: Uint<64>;
  totalTokensAllocated: Uint<128>;
  totalRaised: Uint<128>;
  closeTimestamp: Uint<64>;
}

// ============================================================================
// LEDGER STATE
// ============================================================================

// Launch identifier (shared by both halves of this merged contract)
sealed ledger launchId: Bytes<32>;

// --- from eligibility_gate.compact ---

// Merkle root of the allowlist (governor-updatable for late additions)
export ledger allowlistRoot: Bytes<32>;

// Current phase of the launch (DarkVeil registration/buying vs public curve)
export ledger phase: LaunchPhase;

// Per-user cumulative purchase amount (in token units). This is the SAME
// map both revealBuyCommit (DarkVeil-side) and buyTokens (public-curve-
// side) read/write inline, atomically, keyed by the same in-circuit-
// derived caller identity — see the file header's "known remaining gap"
// note for what this does and doesn't fully cover yet. (Security audit
// fix, the design requirement: the standalone `checkAndUpdateCap` circuit that used to
// also expose this map to an arbitrary caller-supplied key was removed —
// see its former location near checkCap below.)
export ledger cumulativePurchases: Map<Bytes<32>, Uint<128>>;

// Total supply of the launch token (for 5% cap calculation) — distinct
// from `curveSupply` below (tokens actually on the bonding curve).
sealed ledger totalSupply: Uint<128>;

// Maximum per-wallet percentage (5 = 5%)
sealed ledger maxWalletPercent: Uint<8>;

// NIGHT bond amount required for DarkVeil registration
sealed ledger bondAmount: Uint<128>;

// Track locked bonds by user (refundable on cancellation)
export ledger lockedBonds: Map<Bytes<32>, Uint<128>>;

// Nullifier set — prevents double-registration (commitment-nullifier pattern)
export ledger registrationNullifiers: Set<Bytes<32>>;

// Total registrations count
export ledger registrationCount: Counter;

// T22/T43 fix (2026-07-09): whether DarkVeil itself failed (<50%
// participation). Independent of `phase` — under T22's resolution, a
// failed DarkVeil converts the launch to a public-only launch (phase
// advances to Public, not Cancelled), so `claimBondRefund` can't gate on
// `phase == Cancelled` alone or DV registrants on a converted launch would
// have no way to reclaim their bond at all.
export ledger dvFailed: Boolean;

// Precomputed wallet cap (set at deploy time to avoid division in circuit)
sealed ledger walletCap: Uint<128>;

// --- from bonding_curve.compact ---

// Curve parameters (sealed, set at deploy time). Exported (T100 fix,
// 2026-07-22) so off-chain code can compute the real quadratic price from
// these plus tokensSold — see currentPrice()'s removal note below for why
// that computation can't happen on-chain. `sealed` already fully protects
// these from post-construction mutation (verified: it's a write-only
// restriction, checked against every exported circuit and anything
// reachable from one — adding `export` only affects off-chain readability,
// it does not weaken the existing immutability guarantee).
export sealed ledger basePrice: Uint<128>;    // Price at 0% sold, in micro-NIGHT
export sealed ledger maxPrice: Uint<128>;     // Price at 100% sold, in micro-NIGHT
export sealed ledger curveSupply: Uint<128>;  // Total tokens on the bonding curve

// Current state
export ledger curveState: CurveState;

// Unix timestamp (seconds) the curve was activated — 0 while still
// Inactive. Used by expireCurve (T29) to detect a stalled curve; same
// caller-supplies-the-timestamp trust model this file already uses for
// buyTokens's `timestamp` and closeDarkVeil's `closeTimestamp` params —
// Compact circuits have no equivalent of Aiken's tx validity range to
// cross-check against.
export ledger curveActivatedAt: Uint<64>;

// Tokens sold so far
export ledger tokensSold: Uint<128>;

// Total NIGHT raised
export ledger totalRaised: Uint<128>;

// Fee configuration (sealed, set at deploy time)
sealed ledger feeConfig: FeeConfig;

// Creator fee accumulator (goes to creator escrow)
export ledger creatorFees: Uint<128>;

// Treasury fee accumulator
export ledger treasuryFees: Uint<128>;

// Ops fee accumulator
export ledger opsFees: Uint<128>;

// CTO fee-redirect fix (2026-07-12): once a CTO passes via
// cto_governance.compact's SilenceLockTrigger, withdrawFees redirects the
// creator's share to communityWallet instead of creatorAddr — same
// cto_triggered/community-wallet pattern already used by
// lp_escrow.compact/creator_escrow.compact's own triggerCTO/dissolveCTO,
// applied here for the first time to the bonding curve's own fee accrual
// (which holds the REAL claimable creator fee for Tier C — see T45/T46).
// Before this fix, a passed CTO vote never redirected anything here: this
// contract had no CTO concept at all, so the creator could keep receiving
// withdrawFees' creatorAmount share regardless of governance outcome.
export ledger ctoTriggered: Boolean;
export ledger communityWallet: Bytes<32>;

// Token balances (unshielded, keyed by the SAME UserPublicKey identity
// cumulativePurchases/lockedBonds use — see file header's identity note)
export ledger balances: Map<Bytes<32>, Uint<128>>;

// Cumulative gross NIGHT paid per buyer — separate from `balances` (token
// amount) because a refund pays back NIGHT, not tokens.
export ledger paidByBuyer: Map<Bytes<32>, Uint<128>>;

// Buy records (keyed by record ID)
export ledger buyRecords: Map<Bytes<32>, BuyRecord>;

// Buy counter
export ledger buyCount: Counter;

// Governor key (ONE shared identity now — see file header's identity note)
sealed ledger governorKey: Bytes<32>;

// Creator's identity, under the SAME "noctis:user:pk:v1" domain regular
// buyers derive under (the creator connects with an ordinary wallet, same
// as any buyer — this isn't a separate role like governor). Set once at
// deploy from a key computed off-chain. T32: lets registerForDarkVeil,
// revealBuyCommit, and buyTokens all reject the creator's own identity,
// closing CLAUDE.md's DarkVeil eligibility check #3 ("Registrant != creator
// fee-paying wallet address" — never actually implemented before this) and
// the public-curve wash-trading gap in the same pass, since both checks
// are the same comparison against the same field.
sealed ledger creatorKey: Bytes<32>;

// T33: real Midnight unshielded addresses (not derived identities like
// governorKey/creatorKey) that forfeited DarkVeil bond NIGHT gets paid to
// directly via sendUnshielded — set once at deploy, same "caller can't
// redirect the payout" reasoning as everything else in this file that
// takes a fixed address at construction rather than per-call.
sealed ledger treasuryAddr: Bytes<32>;
sealed ledger opsAddr: Bytes<32>;

// Design requirement: withdrawFees previously only
// decremented these fee counters with a comment deferring actual payment
// to "the Zswap layer via transaction merging" — a mechanism that does
// not exist, so every graduated launch's fees were permanently stuck.
// creatorAddr is a real unshielded payout address (distinct from
// creatorKey, which is an identity used for auth/wash-trading checks, not
// a payment destination), same pattern as treasuryAddr/opsAddr above.
sealed ledger creatorAddr: Bytes<32>;

// Design requirement: graduation must never merely flip
// curveState with no circuit ever moving totalRaised anywhere — raised
// NIGHT had no path out of the contract at all. lpEscrowAddr is the real
// unshielded address of this launch's lp_escrow.compact deployment;
// graduateLp() below pays totalRaised there once, guarded by lpSeeded.
sealed ledger lpEscrowAddr: Bytes<32>;
export ledger lpSeeded: Boolean;

// --- from darkveil.compact ---

// DarkVeil's own sub-phase (registration/buying/closed) — see the
// DarkVeilState enum's comment for how this differs from `phase`.
export ledger dvState: DarkVeilState;

// Buy commitments keyed by commitment hash
export ledger commitments: Map<Bytes<32>, BuyCommit>;

// Nullifier set — prevents double-buying during DarkVeil
export ledger buyNullifiers: Set<Bytes<32>>;

// Aggregate stats (public for transparency)
export ledger dvTotalParticipants: Counter;
export ledger totalTokensCommitted: Uint<128>;
export ledger totalRaisedCommitted: Uint<128>;

// DarkVeil allocation (how many tokens are available in this phase)
sealed ledger dvAllocation: Uint<128>;

// Price per token during DarkVeil (fixed price, not bonding curve)
sealed ledger dvPrice: Uint<128>;

// Allowlist size (for participation rate calculation)
sealed ledger allowlistSize: Uint<64>;

// ZK Fair Launch Certificate (set when DarkVeil closes)
export ledger fairLaunchCert: FairLaunchCert;

// Registration close timestamp (for failure path timeout)
sealed ledger registrationCloseTime: Uint<64>;

// T37 resolution (2026-07-13): minimum absolute registrant count required
// before buying can open. Below this, startBuying() rejects and the
// governor must call cancelDarkVeil() instead (T22's existing failure
// path, refundable via claimBondRefund). Defends against two griefing
// vectors a percentage-only check can't catch: (a) a creator's associates
// registering as ghosts to dilute baseSlot for legitimate buyers, and (b)
// an attacker cheaply registering >50% of a tiny launch's participants
// purely to force DV to fail (bonds are refunded on failure, so the only
// real cost is gas). Same fix as eligibility_gate.compact (Tier B).
// CLAUDE.md: MIN_DV_PARTICIPANTS = 15.
sealed ledger minDvParticipants: Uint<64>;

// T43 fix (2026-07-10): per-registrant DarkVeil token allocation —
// CLAUDE.md's `base_slot = dv_supply / registered_count`. This is a FLAT
// per-capita split, the same value for every registrant, not a map — so
// one ledger field is enough. Starts at 0 (meaningless until DV closes);
// set exactly once by closeDarkVeil, computed off-chain (Compact can't
// divide in-circuit) from `dvAllocation / registrationCount` at that
// point, once the final registrant count is known.
export ledger baseSlot: Uint<128>;

// T43 fix: cumulative tokens a buyer actually purchased DURING DarkVeil
// specifically — updated only by revealBuyCommit, kept separate from
// `balances` (which also accrues public-phase purchases) because the
// ratio-based refund formula needs the DarkVeil-only figure, not a buyer's
// combined total.
export ledger dvTokensPurchased: Map<Bytes<32>, Uint<128>>;

// ============================================================================
// WITNESSES
// ============================================================================

witness getUserSecret(): UserSecretKey;
witness getGovernorSecret(): UserSecretKey;

// Merkle proof for allowlist membership — private, stays with prover.
// Depth reduced 32 -> 20 (2026-07-12, T64): a fixed-depth proof always
// walks every level regardless of real registrant count, so depth is a
// direct proving-cost lever, not just a capacity ceiling. 2^20 (1,048,576)
// registrants is far beyond any realistic DarkVeil round (bond + wallet-age
// gated), for 37.5% fewer hash operations per proof than the original 32.
witness getMerkleProof(): Vector<20, MerkleProofEntry>;

// Random nonce for registration commitment — private, prevents replay
witness getRegistrationNonce(): Bytes<32>;

// Random nonce for a DarkVeil buy commitment — private, prevents replay
witness getBuyNonce(): Bytes<32>;

// ============================================================================
// HELPER CIRCUITS
// ============================================================================

// Derive user public key from secret (domain-separated, same pattern as
// FungibleToken). ONE identity for this whole contract now — see file
// header's identity note for why this replaced two separate derivations.
pure circuit deriveUserPublicKey(sk: UserSecretKey): UserPublicKey {
  return UserPublicKey {
    bytes: persistentHash<Vector<2, Bytes<32>>>([
      pad(32, "noctis:user:pk:v1"),
      sk.bytes
    ])
  };
}

// Derive governor public key from secret (domain-separated)
pure circuit deriveGovernorKey(sk: UserSecretKey): Bytes<32> {
  return persistentHash<Vector<2, Bytes<32>>>([
    pad(32, "noctis:governor:pk:v1"),
    sk.bytes
  ]);
}

// Check if a user key is the zero key (invalid)
pure circuit isKeyZero(key: UserPublicKey): Boolean {
  return key == default<UserPublicKey>;
}

// Compute registration commitment from private data
// T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21, Medium): no longer takes a nonce — see
// RegistrationCommitInput's comment for the full finding (a prover-chosen
// nonce made re-registration possible, and lockedBonds.insert overwrites
// rather than accumulates, stranding every duplicate bond but the last).
pure circuit computeRegistrationCommit(
  userKey: Bytes<32>,
  launch: Bytes<32>,
  bond: Uint<128>
): Bytes<32> {
  return persistentHash<RegistrationCommitInput>(RegistrationCommitInput {
    userKey: userKey,
    launchId: launch,
    bondAmount: bond
  });
}

// Verify a price calculation using multiplication only (no division in-circuit)
// Given:  price = basePrice + ((maxPrice - basePrice) * sold^2) / curveSupply^2
// Verify claimedPrice is the FLOOR of that true value:
//   claimedPrice * curveSupply^2 <= basePrice*curveSupply^2 + priceRange*sold^2
//                                 < (claimedPrice + 1) * curveSupply^2
//
// T39 fix (2026-07-09): the previous version checked EXACT equality on Field-
// cast values, which only has a solution when the true price happens to be
// an exact integer — true for a small minority of `sold` values, so most
// real purchases could never construct a passing claimedPrice at all. Field
// only supports == (no <, <=), which is what forced exact equality in the
// first place.
//
// This version avoids Field entirely by declaring every operand at a
// realistic, narrow Uint width, so relational operators stay available for
// a floor-rounding double inequality instead. Compact's non-Field
// multiplication has a real, empirically-confirmed ceiling — NOT simply
// "fits in the target's declared width" as the compiler's own error message
// implies: a same-width-operand multiplication only compiles when the
// RESULT type is Uint<124> or narrower (Uint<125>+ forces the "cast to
// Field" error even when the true value provably fits — confirmed by
// bisection: Uint<122> result compiles, Uint<125> does not, regardless of
// operand width or headroom). Every width below is chosen to respect that
// 124-bit ceiling on each individual multiplication step:
//   curveSupply/sold           <= 2^40  (~1.0995e12, matches the existing
//                                        curveSupply constructor bound)
//   curveSupply^2, sold^2      <= 2^80  (40+40, one mult., well under 124)
//   basePrice/maxPrice/        <= 2^44  (~1.76e13 — vastly more than any
//     claimedPrice/priceRange              realistic microNIGHT price-per-
//                                          token could ever be)
//   price * supply^2           <= 2^124 (44+80, exactly at the ceiling)
// The two 124-bit products are then only ADDED (never multiplied further),
// and addition has no comparable ceiling — the pre-existing, already-
// compiling ledger code in this same file adds two Uint<128> values, so
// summing two Uint<124> values into a Uint<125> is unremarkable by
// comparison. Narrowing casts are runtime-checked (confirmed empirically:
// an out-of-range cast throws, it does not silently wrap), so this is safe
// even if a caller somehow bypassed the bound asserts below.
circuit verifyPrice(
  sold: Uint<128>,
  claimedPrice: Uint<128>
): Boolean {
  assert(disclose(sold <= 1099511627775), "sold exceeds safe range"); // 2^40 - 1
  assert(disclose(claimedPrice <= 17592186044415), "claimedPrice exceeds safe range"); // 2^44 - 1

  const soldN = sold as Uint<40>;
  const curveSupplyN = curveSupply as Uint<40>;
  const claimedPriceN = claimedPrice as Uint<44>;
  const basePriceN = basePrice as Uint<44>;
  const priceRangeN = (maxPrice - basePrice) as Uint<44>;

  const supplySquared = ((curveSupplyN as Uint<80>) * (curveSupplyN as Uint<80>)) as Uint<80>;
  const soldSquared = ((soldN as Uint<80>) * (soldN as Uint<80>)) as Uint<80>;

  const term1 = ((basePriceN as Uint<124>) * (supplySquared as Uint<124>)) as Uint<124>;
  const term2 = ((priceRangeN as Uint<124>) * (soldSquared as Uint<124>)) as Uint<124>;
  const trueValueTimesSupplySquared = ((term1 as Uint<125>) + (term2 as Uint<125>)) as Uint<125>;

  const claimedTimesSupplySquared = ((claimedPriceN as Uint<124>) * (supplySquared as Uint<124>)) as Uint<124>;
  const nextClaimedTimesSupplySquared =
    ((claimedTimesSupplySquared as Uint<125>) + (supplySquared as Uint<125>)) as Uint<125>;

  return disclose(
    (claimedTimesSupplySquared as Uint<125>) <= trueValueTimesSupplySquared
      && trueValueTimesSupplySquared < nextClaimedTimesSupplySquared
  );
}

// Verify a claimed fee slice is the FLOOR of grossAmount * bps / 10000:
//   claimedFee * 10000 <= grossAmount * bps < (claimedFee + 1) * 10000
//
// T39 fix (2026-07-09): same floor-rounding pattern as verifyPrice, same
// reason — exact equality had no solution for most grossAmount values, and
// same 124-bit-per-multiplication ceiling applies (see verifyPrice's
// comment for how that ceiling was found). grossAmount is bounded by
// tokenAmount(<=2^40) * claimedPrice(<=2^44), so <= 2^84; bps is a small
// constant (40/60/100 in practice, Uint<16> declared, real max needed is
// ~14 bits for the 10000 denominator). Every product here — 84+16=100 and
// 84+14=98 — sits comfortably under the 124 ceiling.
// Phase 5 hygiene fix (2026-07-12): marked pure — depends only on its own
// parameters, no ledger or witness access.
pure circuit verifyFeeSlice(
  grossAmount: Uint<128>,
  bps: Uint<16>,
  claimedFee: Uint<128>
): Boolean {
  assert(disclose(grossAmount <= 19342813113834066795298815), "grossAmount exceeds safe range"); // 2^84 - 1
  assert(disclose(claimedFee <= 19342813113834066795298815), "claimedFee exceeds safe range"); // 2^84 - 1

  const grossN = grossAmount as Uint<84>;
  const claimedFeeN = claimedFee as Uint<84>;

  const product = ((grossN as Uint<100>) * (bps as Uint<100>)) as Uint<100>;
  const claimedTimesDenom = ((claimedFeeN as Uint<98>) * (10000 as Uint<98>)) as Uint<98>;
  const nextClaimedTimesDenom = ((claimedTimesDenom as Uint<100>) + (10000 as Uint<100>)) as Uint<100>;

  return disclose(
    (claimedTimesDenom as Uint<100>) <= product && product < nextClaimedTimesDenom
  );
}

// T43 fix (2026-07-10): verify a claimed ratio-based NIGHT bond refund is
// the FLOOR of `bonded * purchased / allocated`:
//   claimedRefund * allocated <= bonded * purchased < (claimedRefund + 1) * allocated
// Same floor-rounding double-inequality pattern as verifyPrice/
// verifyFeeSlice (T39) — the caller computes the true value off-chain
// (where real division is fine) and this circuit verifies the floor,
// since Compact can't divide in-circuit. Covers every case CLAUDE.md's
// formula describes with the same formula, no special-casing needed:
// purchased == allocated -> refund == bonded (100% back); purchased == 0
// -> refund == 0 (ghost, fully forfeited); anything between is the
// proportional partial return.
// Phase 5 hygiene fix (2026-07-12): marked pure — depends only on its own
// parameters, no ledger or witness access.
pure circuit verifyRatioRefund(
  bonded: Uint<128>,
  purchased: Uint<128>,
  allocated: Uint<128>,
  claimedRefund: Uint<128>
): Boolean {
  assert(disclose(allocated > 0), "allocated must be positive"); // baseSlot must have been set
  assert(disclose(purchased <= allocated), "purchased cannot exceed allocated");
  assert(disclose(bonded <= 17592186044415), "bonded exceeds safe range"); // 2^44 - 1
  assert(disclose(purchased <= 1099511627775), "purchased exceeds safe range"); // 2^40 - 1
  assert(disclose(allocated <= 1099511627775), "allocated exceeds safe range"); // 2^40 - 1
  assert(disclose(claimedRefund <= 17592186044415), "claimedRefund exceeds safe range"); // 2^44 - 1

  const bondedN = bonded as Uint<44>;
  const purchasedN = purchased as Uint<40>;
  const allocatedN = allocated as Uint<40>;
  const claimedRefundN = claimedRefund as Uint<44>;

  // bonded(44) * purchased(40) = 84 bits, well under the 124-bit ceiling
  const bondedTimesPurchased = ((bondedN as Uint<84>) * (purchasedN as Uint<84>)) as Uint<84>;
  // claimedRefund(44) * allocated(40) = 84 bits, same headroom
  const claimedTimesAllocated = ((claimedRefundN as Uint<84>) * (allocatedN as Uint<84>)) as Uint<84>;
  const nextClaimedTimesAllocated = ((claimedTimesAllocated as Uint<85>) + (allocatedN as Uint<85>)) as Uint<85>;

  return disclose(
    (claimedTimesAllocated as Uint<85>) <= (bondedTimesPurchased as Uint<85>)
      && (bondedTimesPurchased as Uint<85>) < nextClaimedTimesAllocated
  );
}

// --- from darkveil.compact ---

// Compute buy commitment from private data
pure circuit computeBuyCommit(
  buyerKey: Bytes<32>,
  launch: Bytes<32>,
  tokenAmount: Uint<128>,
  pricePerToken: Uint<128>,
  nonce: Bytes<32>
): Bytes<32> {
  return persistentHash<BuyCommitInput>(BuyCommitInput {
    buyerKey: buyerKey,
    launchId: launch,
    tokenAmount: tokenAmount,
    pricePerToken: pricePerToken,
    nonce: nonce
  });
}

// Compute nullifier — unique per (buyer, launch), prevents double-buying
// without revealing which buyer is associated with which commitment
// T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21, High): no longer called by submitBuyCommit/
// cancelBuyCommit — see computeBuyNullifier below.
pure circuit computeNullifier(
  buyerKey: Bytes<32>,
  launch: Bytes<32>
): Bytes<32> {
  return persistentHash<NullifierInput>(NullifierInput {
    buyerKey: buyerKey,
    launchId: launch
  });
}

// T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21, Compact security-review pass — High): same
// finding and fix as eligibility_gate.compact's computeBuyNullifier (this
// merged Tier C contract has its own identical copy of the guarded
// circuit) — the buy nullifier used to be a free caller-supplied parameter
// on submitBuyCommit, letting a single registrant submit unlimited buy
// commitments, and computeNullifier's public inputs made every registrant's
// nullifier precomputable by anyone. Fixed by deriving from the caller's
// SECRET key bytes instead of their public derived key.
pure circuit computeBuyNullifier(
  buyerSecret: Bytes<32>,
  launch: Bytes<32>
): Bytes<32> {
  return persistentHash<BuyNullifierInput>(BuyNullifierInput {
    domain: pad(32, "noctis:dv:buy:nullifier:v1"),
    buyerSecret: buyerSecret,
    launchId: launch
  });
}

// Compute certificate hash
pure circuit computeCertHash(
  launch: Bytes<32>,
  participants: Uint<64>,
  tokensAllocated: Uint<128>,
  raised: Uint<128>,
  closeTime: Uint<64>
): Bytes<32> {
  return persistentHash<CertHashInput>(CertHashInput {
    launchId: launch,
    totalParticipants: participants,
    totalTokensAllocated: tokensAllocated,
    totalRaised: raised,
    closeTimestamp: closeTime
  });
}

// ============================================================================
// CONSTRUCTOR
// ============================================================================

constructor(
  launchId_: Bytes<32>,
  allowlistRoot_: Bytes<32>,
  totalSupply_: Uint<128>,
  maxWalletPercent_: Uint<8>,
  bondAmount_: Uint<128>,
  walletCap_: Uint<128>,
  basePrice_: Uint<128>,
  maxPrice_: Uint<128>,
  curveSupply_: Uint<128>,
  dvAllocation_: Uint<128>,
  dvPrice_: Uint<128>,
  allowlistSize_: Uint<64>,
  registrationCloseTime_: Uint<64>,
  minDvParticipants_: Uint<64>,
  creatorPubKey_: Bytes<32>,
  treasuryAddr_: Bytes<32>,
  opsAddr_: Bytes<32>,
  creatorAddr_: Bytes<32>,
  lpEscrowAddr_: Bytes<32>
) {
  // Sanity bound on curveSupply so curveSupply^2 * priceRange in verifyPrice
  // can't be pushed into Uint<128> overflow by a misconfigured deploy.
  assert(disclose(curveSupply_ > 0 && curveSupply_ <= 1000000000000), "curveSupply out of safe range");
  assert(disclose(maxPrice_ > basePrice_), "maxPrice must exceed basePrice");
  assert(disclose(maxPrice_ <= 17592186044415), "maxPrice out of safe range"); // 2^44 - 1

  launchId = disclose(launchId_);
  allowlistRoot = disclose(allowlistRoot_);
  totalSupply = disclose(totalSupply_);
  maxWalletPercent = disclose(maxWalletPercent_);
  bondAmount = disclose(bondAmount_);

  // walletCap MUST equal totalSupply * maxWalletPercent / 100, computed
  // off-chain (Compact circuits can't divide) and passed in directly. See
  // T38's fix history for why this assert exists (a prior version computed
  // this on-chain with the division silently dropped, disabling the cap).
  assert(disclose(walletCap_ > 0), "walletCap must be positive");
  walletCap = disclose(walletCap_);

  basePrice = disclose(basePrice_);
  maxPrice = disclose(maxPrice_);
  curveSupply = disclose(curveSupply_);

  // Set fee config: 1.0% creator + 0.6% treasury + 0.4% ops = 2.0% total
  feeConfig = disclose(FeeConfig {
    creatorBps: 100,
    treasuryBps: 60,
    opsBps: 40,
    totalBps: 200
  });

  // Set governor from deployer's secret (ONE derivation for the whole
  // merged contract — see file header's identity note)
  const govSecret = getGovernorSecret();
  const govKey = deriveGovernorKey(govSecret);
  governorKey = disclose(govKey);
  creatorKey = disclose(creatorPubKey_);
  treasuryAddr = disclose(treasuryAddr_);
  opsAddr = disclose(opsAddr_);
  creatorAddr = disclose(creatorAddr_);
  lpEscrowAddr = disclose(lpEscrowAddr_);
  lpSeeded = disclose(false);
  ctoTriggered = disclose(false);
  communityWallet = disclose(pad(32, ""));

  phase = LaunchPhase.Pending;
  dvFailed = disclose(false);
  curveState = CurveState.Inactive;
  curveActivatedAt = 0;
  tokensSold = 0;
  totalRaised = 0;
  creatorFees = 0;
  treasuryFees = 0;
  opsFees = 0;

  // --- from darkveil.compact ---
  dvAllocation = disclose(dvAllocation_);
  dvPrice = disclose(dvPrice_);
  allowlistSize = disclose(allowlistSize_);
  registrationCloseTime = disclose(registrationCloseTime_);
  assert(disclose(minDvParticipants_ > 0), "minDvParticipants must be positive");
  minDvParticipants = disclose(minDvParticipants_);
  dvState = DarkVeilState.Inactive;
  totalTokensCommitted = 0;
  totalRaisedCommitted = 0;
  baseSlot = 0; // meaningless until closeDarkVeil sets it (T43)
  fairLaunchCert = disclose(FairLaunchCert {
    launchId: launchId_,
    totalParticipants: 0,
    totalTokensAllocated: 0,
    totalRaised: 0,
    participationRate: 0,
    closeTimestamp: 0,
    certHash: pad(32, "")
  });
}

// ============================================================================
// CIRCUITS — ALLOWLIST VERIFICATION
// ============================================================================

// Verify allowlist membership via a real 20-level Merkle inclusion proof
// (witness-based, privacy-preserving — only the root is public; a user's
// own leaf and path are never revealed to anyone but the prover). T42 fix
// (2026-07-09) — see contracts/midnight's other T42 writeups for the full
// fixed-depth-tree convention this depends on. Depth reduced 32 -> 20,
// T64, 2026-07-12 — see getMerkleProof's witness declaration comment.
//
// Design requirement: the leaf is never a free witness
// (getAllowlistLeaf()) with nothing tying it to the caller — any caller
// could supply ANY real leaf from the tree (e.g. copy another registrant's
// leaf + proof) and pass membership as someone else. The leaf is now
// derived in-circuit from the caller's own identity, so a valid proof can
// only be constructed by whoever controls the secret behind `caller`. The
// off-chain allowlist tree must be built with each leaf as
// hashAllowlistLeaf(registrantPubKey) — see packages/zk-proofs's paired
// helper.
circuit verifyAllowlist(caller: Bytes<32>): [] {
  const leaf = persistentHash<Vector<2, Bytes<32>>>([
    pad(32, "noctis:allowlist:leaf:v1"),
    caller
  ]);
  const proof = getMerkleProof();

  const recomputedRoot = fold(
    (acc: Bytes<32>, entry: MerkleProofEntry): Bytes<32> => {
      const left = disclose(entry.goesLeft) ? acc : entry.sibling;
      const right = disclose(entry.goesLeft) ? entry.sibling : acc;
      return persistentHash<AllowlistNodeInput>(AllowlistNodeInput {
        domain: pad(32, "noctis:allowlist:node:v1"),
        left: left,
        right: right
      });
    },
    leaf,
    proof
  );

  assert(disclose(recomputedRoot == allowlistRoot), "Invalid allowlist proof");
}

// ============================================================================
// CIRCUITS — DARKVEIL REGISTRATION
// ============================================================================

// Register for DarkVeil phase
// 1. Verify allowlist membership
// 2. Verify NIGHT bond is provided
// 3. Lock the bond (refundable on cancellation)
// 4. Emit nullifier to prevent double-registration
export circuit registerForDarkVeil(
  bondCommitment: Bytes<32>
): [] {
  // Must be in DarkVeil phase
  assert(disclose(phase == LaunchPhase.DarkVeil), "DarkVeil registration not active");
  // T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21, Medium): `phase` alone was checked, never
  // `dvState` — see eligibility_gate.compact's parallel fix comment for
  // the full finding (this merged Tier C contract has the same bug).
  assert(disclose(dvState == DarkVeilState.Registration), "DarkVeil not in registration sub-phase");

  // Derive caller identity (moved above verifyAllowlist — security audit
  // fix the design requirement needs the caller bytes to derive the allowlist leaf)
  const sk = getUserSecret();
  const caller = deriveUserPublicKey(sk);
  assert(disclose(!isKeyZero(caller)), "Invalid user key");

  // Verify allowlist membership, bound to this specific caller
  verifyAllowlist(caller.bytes);

  // T32 / CLAUDE.md eligibility check #3: registrant != creator
  assert(disclose(caller.bytes != creatorKey), "Creator cannot register for DarkVeil");

  // Compute registration commitment (nullifier) — T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21):
  // no longer takes a nonce, see computeRegistrationCommit's own comment.
  const nullifier = computeRegistrationCommit(
    caller.bytes,
    launchId,
    bondAmount
  );

  // Prevent double-registration (commitment-nullifier pattern)
  assert(
    !registrationNullifiers.member(disclose(nullifier)),
    "Already registered for this launch"
  );
  registrationNullifiers.insert(disclose(nullifier));

  // T40 fix (2026-07-09): require the NIGHT bond to actually be paid.
  receiveUnshielded(nativeToken(), disclose(bondAmount));

  // Lock the NIGHT bond
  lockedBonds.insert(disclose(caller.bytes), disclose(bondAmount));

  // Track registration count
  registrationCount.increment(1);
}

// ============================================================================
// CIRCUITS — DARKVEIL PRIVATE BUY (from darkveil.compact)
// ============================================================================

// Submit a private buy commitment during the DarkVeil buying phase.
// The commitment hides the purchase amount and buyer identity — no payment
// happens here, deliberately: checking payment now would require disclosing
// the amount to receiveUnshielded, defeating the point of committing before
// revealing. See this file's header for the full reasoning.
//
// Phase 4 fix (2026-07-12): previously ANY caller could submit a buy
// commitment with no proof of prior DarkVeil registration at all, bypassing
// the wallet-age/allowlist/NIGHT-bond eligibility gate entirely. Fixed by
// requiring the caller to recompute their OWN registration nullifier (same
// secret + same registration nonce + bondAmount used at
// registerForDarkVeil) and prove it's already a member of
// registrationNullifiers — this proves prior registration without
// revealing WHICH registrant is buying (a nullifier is already a one-way,
// unlinkable value, and this one is already public from registration),
// preserving the commit-time identity-blindness this circuit is designed
// around. Same fix applied identically to Tier B's eligibility_gate.compact.
// T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21, High): nullifier is no longer a caller-supplied
// parameter — see computeBuyNullifier's own comment for the full finding.
export circuit submitBuyCommit(
  commitment: Bytes<32>,
  timestamp: Uint<64>
): [] {
  assert(disclose(dvState == DarkVeilState.Buying), "DarkVeil buying not active");

  const sk = getUserSecret();
  const caller = deriveUserPublicKey(sk);
  // T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21): no longer takes a regNonce, see
  // computeRegistrationCommit's own comment.
  const regNullifier = computeRegistrationCommit(caller.bytes, launchId, bondAmount);
  assert(
    disclose(registrationNullifiers.member(disclose(regNullifier))),
    "Not a registered DarkVeil participant"
  );

  assert(
    !commitments.member(disclose(commitment)),
    "Commitment already exists"
  );

  const nullifier = computeBuyNullifier(sk.bytes, launchId);
  assert(
    !buyNullifiers.member(disclose(nullifier)),
    "Already bought in this DarkVeil phase"
  );
  buyNullifiers.insert(disclose(nullifier));

  commitments.insert(disclose(commitment), disclose(BuyCommit {
    commitment: commitment,
    nullifier: nullifier,
    timestamp: timestamp,
    status: CommitStatus.Open
  }));

  dvTotalParticipants.increment(1);
}

// Reveal a buy commitment (after DarkVeil closes) — this is when the
// actual purchase amount becomes public, by design (see PRIVACY ANALYSIS).
//
// T25 follow-up fix (2026-07-10), two gaps closed in the same circuit:
//   1. Payment enforcement — this file's header explains why it belongs
//      HERE rather than at submitBuyCommit: the amount is already about to
//      become public at this exact point, so requiring receiveUnshielded
//      here discloses nothing beyond what revealing already does.
//   2. Cumulative cap enforcement — DarkVeil purchases now count toward
//      the same cumulativePurchases map buyTokens (public phase) reads
//      and writes inline, closing T25's previously "known remaining gap."
// T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21, Compact security-review pass): revealBuyCommit
// previously took real NIGHT via receiveUnshielded and accrued it ONLY into
// totalRaisedCommitted — a field nothing in this file ever pays out
// (grep-confirmed: zero sendUnshielded call references it). Every real
// DarkVeil purchase's proceeds were permanently locked in the contract with
// no exit, and DarkVeil buyers had no claimCurveRefund path either (that
// circuit only reads paidByBuyer, which only buyTokens ever wrote to).
// Fixed by mirroring buyTokens' exact fee-verification/accrual/payment
// pattern: claimedCreatorFee/claimedTreasuryFee/claimedOpsFee are now real
// parameters, verified via the same verifyFeeSlice cross-multiplication
// check, accrued into the SAME creatorFees/treasuryFees/opsFees counters
// withdrawFees already pays out, with the net (post-fee) proceeds added to
// totalRaised (the same field graduateLp already sends to the LP escrow) —
// so DarkVeil and public-phase proceeds now share one real payout path.
// totalRaisedCommitted is left untouched in meaning (still the gross
// DarkVeil-phase statistic the Fair Launch Certificate reads) — this fix
// adds a REAL, separate flow into totalRaised, it does not repurpose the
// existing field. paidByBuyer is now also credited so a DarkVeil buyer can
// claimCurveRefund if the curve is later cancelled, same as a public buyer.
// T-AUDIT note (2026-07-21, Low): this circuit has no reveal deadline —
// dvState only needs to be Closed, with no upper bound on how long after
// close a commitment can still be revealed. A buyer who never reveals
// simply never pays and never receives tokens (their commitment stays
// Open forever); this doesn't lock funds or break accounting, it's a
// liveness/UX gap (stale open commitments accumulate) rather than a
// security issue. Not fixed here — would need a new sealed deadline field
// and off-chain coordination for what happens to a commitment that expires
// unrevealed, a product decision rather than a quick patch.
export circuit revealBuyCommit(
  commitment: Bytes<32>,
  tokenAmount: Uint<128>,
  pricePerToken: Uint<128>,
  claimedCreatorFee: Uint<128>,
  claimedTreasuryFee: Uint<128>,
  claimedOpsFee: Uint<128>
): [] {
  assert(disclose(dvState == DarkVeilState.Closed), "DarkVeil not closed");

  assert(commitments.member(disclose(commitment)), "Commitment not found");
  const commit = commitments.lookup(disclose(commitment));
  assert(disclose(commit.status == CommitStatus.Open), "Commitment already revealed");

  // Verify the caller owns this commitment by recomputing it
  const sk = getUserSecret();
  const caller = deriveUserPublicKey(sk);
  const nonce = getBuyNonce();
  const recomputed = computeBuyCommit(
    caller.bytes,
    launchId,
    tokenAmount,
    pricePerToken,
    nonce
  );
  assert(disclose(recomputed == commitment), "Not the commitment owner");
  // T32: same identity check as registerForDarkVeil, at zero extra
  // disclosure cost — caller is already bound to this tx via the
  // commitment-ownership proof above, same reasoning this circuit already
  // uses for enforcing payment at reveal time (see file header).
  assert(disclose(caller.bytes != creatorKey), "Creator cannot buy their own DarkVeil allocation");

  // Verify the price matches DarkVeil price
  assert(disclose(pricePerToken == dvPrice), "Price mismatch with DarkVeil price");

  // Security-audit fix (Phase 2): darkveil.compact's standalone Tier B
  // copy of this circuit already enforces this per-registrant cap
  // (design requirement) — this merged Tier C copy set/read baseSlot for the
  // ratio-refund formula but never enforced it as a purchase-time ceiling,
  // so a single registrant could reveal up to the entire dvAllocation pool
  // in one call, bounded only by the coarser 5% wallet cap below.
  assert(disclose(tokenAmount <= baseSlot), "Exceeds per-registrant DarkVeil allocation");

  // Verify tokens don't exceed the DarkVeil allocation pool
  const newTotal = (totalTokensCommitted + tokenAmount) as Uint<128>;
  assert(disclose(newTotal <= dvAllocation), "Exceeds DarkVeil allocation");

  // T25 fix: enforce the 5% cumulative wallet cap — same map, same
  // walletCap, same identity buyTokens uses for the public phase.
  const priorCumulative = cumulativePurchases.member(disclose(caller.bytes))
    ? cumulativePurchases.lookup(disclose(caller.bytes))
    : 0;
  const newCumulative = (priorCumulative + tokenAmount) as Uint<128>;
  assert(disclose(newCumulative <= walletCap), "Purchase exceeds 5% wallet cap");
  cumulativePurchases.insert(disclose(caller.bytes), disclose(newCumulative));

  // T25 fix: require the NIGHT payment to actually be paid — grossPayment
  // is tokenAmount * pricePerToken, exact (no rounding), same Field-based
  // multiplication this circuit already used for totalRaisedCommitted.
  const grossPaymentF = ((tokenAmount as Field) * (pricePerToken as Field)) as Field;
  const grossPayment = grossPaymentF as Uint<128>;

  // T-AUDIT fix: verify each claimed fee slice against the same fee config
  // buyTokens uses — closes the "DarkVeil proceeds have no real payout"
  // Critical finding (see this circuit's own header comment above).
  assert(disclose(verifyFeeSlice(grossPayment, feeConfig.creatorBps, claimedCreatorFee)), "Creator fee mismatch");
  assert(disclose(verifyFeeSlice(grossPayment, feeConfig.treasuryBps, claimedTreasuryFee)), "Treasury fee mismatch");
  assert(disclose(verifyFeeSlice(grossPayment, feeConfig.opsBps, claimedOpsFee)), "Ops fee mismatch");

  receiveUnshielded(nativeToken(), disclose(grossPayment));

  const feeTotal = ((claimedCreatorFee + claimedTreasuryFee) + claimedOpsFee) as Uint<128>;
  const netPayment = (grossPayment - feeTotal) as Uint<128>;

  creatorFees = disclose((creatorFees + claimedCreatorFee) as Uint<128>);
  treasuryFees = disclose((treasuryFees + claimedTreasuryFee) as Uint<128>);
  opsFees = disclose((opsFees + claimedOpsFee) as Uint<128>);

  // Update aggregate stats — totalRaisedCommitted stays the gross DarkVeil
  // statistic (unchanged meaning, still read by the Fair Launch
  // Certificate); totalRaised is the REAL, withdrawable accumulator
  // graduateLp already pays to the LP escrow, now shared by both phases.
  totalTokensCommitted = disclose(newTotal);
  totalRaisedCommitted = disclose((totalRaisedCommitted + grossPayment) as Uint<128>);
  totalRaised = disclose((totalRaised + netPayment) as Uint<128>);

  // Credit tokens to buyer's balance — same map buyTokens credits, so a
  // buyer's DarkVeil + public holdings show up in one place.
  const currentBal = balances.member(disclose(caller.bytes))
    ? balances.lookup(disclose(caller.bytes))
    : 0;
  balances.insert(disclose(caller.bytes), disclose((currentBal + tokenAmount) as Uint<128>));

  // T-AUDIT fix: track cumulative NIGHT paid, same map buyTokens uses, so a
  // DarkVeil buyer can claimCurveRefund() if the curve is later cancelled —
  // previously only public buyers had a refund path.
  const currentPaid = paidByBuyer.member(disclose(caller.bytes))
    ? paidByBuyer.lookup(disclose(caller.bytes))
    : 0;
  paidByBuyer.insert(disclose(caller.bytes), disclose((currentPaid + grossPayment) as Uint<128>));

  // T43 fix: also track DarkVeil-ONLY purchases, separate from `balances`
  // (which mixes in public-phase purchases too) — the ratio-based bond
  // refund formula needs this DarkVeil-only figure specifically.
  const currentDvPurchased = dvTokensPurchased.member(disclose(caller.bytes))
    ? dvTokensPurchased.lookup(disclose(caller.bytes))
    : 0;
  dvTokensPurchased.insert(disclose(caller.bytes), disclose((currentDvPurchased + tokenAmount) as Uint<128>));

  // Mark commitment as revealed
  commitments.insert(disclose(commitment), disclose(BuyCommit {
    commitment: commit.commitment,
    nullifier: commit.nullifier,
    timestamp: commit.timestamp,
    status: CommitStatus.Revealed
  }));
}

// Cancel a buy commitment (before DarkVeil closes) — only the commitment
// owner can cancel. No payment to refund here, since none was taken at
// submit time (see submitBuyCommit's comment).
export circuit cancelBuyCommit(commitment: Bytes<32>): [] {
  assert(disclose(dvState == DarkVeilState.Buying), "Can only cancel during buying phase");

  assert(commitments.member(disclose(commitment)), "Commitment not found");
  const commit = commitments.lookup(disclose(commitment));
  assert(disclose(commit.status == CommitStatus.Open), "Commitment not open");

  // Verify ownership via the nullifier (derived from the secret key —
  // T-AUDIT fix, 2026-07-21, must match submitBuyCommit's derivation).
  const sk = getUserSecret();
  const expectedNullifier = computeBuyNullifier(sk.bytes, launchId);
  assert(disclose(expectedNullifier == commit.nullifier), "Not the commitment owner");

  commitments.insert(disclose(commitment), disclose(BuyCommit {
    commitment: commit.commitment,
    nullifier: commit.nullifier,
    timestamp: commit.timestamp,
    status: CommitStatus.Cancelled
  }));

  buyNullifiers.remove(disclose(commit.nullifier));
  dvTotalParticipants.decrement(1);
}

// ============================================================================
// CIRCUITS — ZK FAIR LAUNCH CERTIFICATE (from darkveil.compact)
// ============================================================================

// Close DarkVeil and generate the ZK Fair Launch Certificate (governor
// only — called after the buying phase ends).
//
// T43 fix (2026-07-10): also takes `baseSlot_`, the per-registrant
// DarkVeil allocation (CLAUDE.md's `base_slot = dv_supply / registered_count`).
// Computed off-chain by the governor from `dvAllocation / registrationCount`
// at this exact moment — the final registrant count is only known once
// registration is over, which is why this can't be set any earlier (e.g.
// in the constructor). Sealed here, read by claimRatioBondRefund below.
export circuit closeDarkVeil(closeTimestamp: Uint<64>, baseSlot_: Uint<128>): [] {
  assert(disclose(dvState == DarkVeilState.Buying), "DarkVeil not in buying phase");

  const govSecret = getGovernorSecret();
  const govKey = deriveGovernorKey(govSecret);
  assert(disclose(govKey == governorKey), "Only governor can close DarkVeil");

  assert(disclose(baseSlot_ > 0), "baseSlot must be positive");
  // T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21, Medium): same unvalidated-baseSlot finding as
  // eligibility_gate.compact — see that circuit's parallel fix comment.
  const totalAllocatedF = ((baseSlot_ as Field) * (registrationCount.read() as Field)) as Field;
  const totalAllocated = totalAllocatedF as Uint<128>;
  assert(disclose(totalAllocated <= dvAllocation), "baseSlot * registrationCount exceeds dvAllocation");
  baseSlot = disclose(baseSlot_);

  dvState = DarkVeilState.Closed;

  const certHash = computeCertHash(
    launchId,
    dvTotalParticipants.read(),
    totalTokensCommitted,
    totalRaisedCommitted,
    closeTimestamp
  );

  fairLaunchCert = disclose(FairLaunchCert {
    launchId: launchId,
    totalParticipants: dvTotalParticipants.read(),
    totalTokensAllocated: totalTokensCommitted,
    totalRaised: totalRaisedCommitted,
    participationRate: 0, // Computed off-chain from raw numbers (no division in-circuit)
    closeTimestamp: closeTimestamp,
    certHash: certHash
  });
}

// Get the ZK Fair Launch Certificate (public, for display and verification)
export circuit getFairLaunchCert(): FairLaunchCert {
  return disclose(fairLaunchCert);
}

// ============================================================================
// CIRCUITS — DARKVEIL VIEW / READ (from darkveil.compact)
// ============================================================================

export circuit getDvState(): DarkVeilState {
  return dvState;
}

export circuit getTotalCommitted(): Uint<128> {
  return totalTokensCommitted;
}

export circuit getTotalRaisedCommitted(): Uint<128> {
  return totalRaisedCommitted;
}

export circuit getDvAllocation(): Uint<128> {
  return dvAllocation;
}

export circuit getDvPrice(): Uint<128> {
  return dvPrice;
}

// ============================================================================
// CIRCUITS — DARKVEIL ADMIN (from darkveil.compact)
// ============================================================================

// Start DarkVeil registration — governor only. Distinct from advancePhase:
// this toggles the finer-grained dvState sub-phase, not the overall
// LaunchPhase (which advancePhase already handles separately).
export circuit startRegistration(): [] {
  const govSecret = getGovernorSecret();
  const govKey = deriveGovernorKey(govSecret);
  assert(disclose(govKey == governorKey), "Only governor can start");
  assert(disclose(dvState == DarkVeilState.Inactive), "DarkVeil already started");
  dvState = DarkVeilState.Registration;
}

// Start DarkVeil buying — governor only.
export circuit startBuying(): [] {
  const govSecret = getGovernorSecret();
  const govKey = deriveGovernorKey(govSecret);
  assert(disclose(govKey == governorKey), "Only governor can start buying");
  assert(disclose(dvState == DarkVeilState.Registration), "Must be in registration phase");
  // T37: refuse to open buying below the minimum registrant floor — the
  // governor must call cancelDarkVeil() instead, which is fully refundable.
  assert(
    disclose(registrationCount.read() >= minDvParticipants),
    "Below minimum DarkVeil participant threshold — cancel instead"
  );
  dvState = DarkVeilState.Buying;
}

// Cancel DarkVeil (failure path — T22 resolution). Bonds are refundable
// via claimBondRefund (this same contract now, for Tier C).
export circuit cancelDarkVeil(): [] {
  const govSecret = getGovernorSecret();
  const govKey = deriveGovernorKey(govSecret);
  assert(disclose(govKey == governorKey), "Only governor can cancel");
  assert(disclose(dvState != DarkVeilState.Closed), "Already closed");
  assert(disclose(dvState != DarkVeilState.Cancelled), "Already cancelled");
  dvState = DarkVeilState.Cancelled;
}

// ============================================================================
// CIRCUITS — CUMULATIVE CAP TRACKING (T25)
// ============================================================================

// Check and update the per-wallet 5% cumulative cap. Kept as its own public
// circuit (not just inlined into buyTokens) since off-chain DarkVeil
// tooling may still want to call this directly during the DarkVeil phase —
// though see the file header's "known remaining gap" note: darkveil.compact
// itself does not call this today, so DarkVeil purchases aren't actually
// routed through here yet.
// Design requirement: this circuit used to be exported here as
// well, taking an arbitrary caller-supplied `callerKey` with no
// authorization and no payment, which would not have bound the
// identity's cap by writing cumulativePurchases[callerKey] directly. It
// was already dead code in THIS contract — buyTokens and revealBuyCommit
// both do their own inline atomic cap check/update against this same map,
// keyed by their own in-circuit-derived caller identity (see the T25 cap
// enforcement above and in revealBuyCommit) — so it's removed rather than
// fixed in place. eligibility_gate.compact's standalone copy (used by
// Tier B, which has no equivalent inline check) keeps the circuit but
// binds callerKey to the derived caller identity instead of accepting it
// as a parameter.

// Check cap without updating (read-only, for UI queries)
export circuit checkCap(callerKey: Bytes<32>): Uint<128> {
  const current = cumulativePurchases.member(disclose(callerKey))
    ? cumulativePurchases.lookup(disclose(callerKey))
    : 0;
  return disclose(current);
}

// ============================================================================
// CIRCUITS — BOND REFUND (T22 resolution — DarkVeil failure path)
// ============================================================================

// Claim a FULL NIGHT bond refund — launch was cancelled outright, OR
// DarkVeil itself failed and the launch converted to public (T22
// resolution). For a DarkVeil that closed NORMALLY (succeeded), see
// claimRatioBondRefund below instead — that's a different formula, not
// this one.
//
// T43 fix (2026-07-10): now actually pays the NIGHT back via
// sendUnshielded (same verified builtin claimCurveRefund already uses),
// instead of only clearing the ledger entry. Needs a real recipient
// address, same reasoning as claimCurveRefund's recipientAddr param.
export circuit claimBondRefund(recipientAddr: Bytes<32>): [] {
  assert(
    disclose(phase == LaunchPhase.Cancelled || dvFailed),
    "Launch not cancelled and DarkVeil did not fail"
  );

  const sk = getUserSecret();
  const caller = deriveUserPublicKey(sk);
  assert(disclose(!isKeyZero(caller)), "Invalid user key");
  // Phase 5 hygiene fix (2026-07-12): sanity-check the caller-supplied
  // payout destination isn't the empty/all-zero address — guards against a
  // fat-fingered recipientAddr silently burning the refund.
  assert(disclose(recipientAddr != pad(32, "")), "Recipient address cannot be empty");

  assert(
    lockedBonds.member(disclose(caller.bytes)),
    "No locked bond found for caller"
  );

  const bond = lockedBonds.lookup(disclose(caller.bytes));
  assert(disclose(bond > 0), "Bond already claimed");

  // Clear before paying out (checks-effects-interactions, same ordering
  // claimCurveRefund uses).
  lockedBonds.insert(disclose(caller.bytes), disclose(0));

  const dest = right<ContractAddress, UserAddress>(disclose(UserAddress { bytes: recipientAddr }));
  sendUnshielded(nativeToken(), disclose(bond), dest);
}

// Claim a RATIO-BASED partial NIGHT bond refund — for a DarkVeil that
// closed NORMALLY (succeeded, not cancelled, not marked failed). CLAUDE.md:
// `NIGHT_returned = NIGHT_bonded * tokens_purchased / tokens_allocated`.
// Bought 100% of the flat per-capita allocation (baseSlot) -> full refund;
// bought 0% (ghost registrant) -> fully forfeited; anything between is
// proportional. `claimedRefund` is computed off-chain (real division is
// fine there) and verified on-chain as the floor of the true value via
// verifyRatioRefund — same pattern as every other caller-supplies-a-claim
// circuit in this file.
//
// T33 fix (2026-07-10): the forfeited remainder (bond - claimedRefund) is
// now actually routed, not left unpaid. Split 60% treasury / 40% ops —
// same ratio D5 already established for launch fee splits, reused here
// rather than inventing a new one. `claimedTreasuryShare` is
// caller-supplied and verified as the floor of `forfeited * 6000/10000`
// via the existing verifyFeeSlice helper (bps-generic, already used for
// buyTokens's fee splits); `opsShare` is computed on-chain as the exact
// remainder (`forfeited - claimedTreasuryShare`) so no NIGHT is lost to
// floor-rounding dust the way a second independent floor check could.
// `verifyRatioRefund` already guarantees `claimedRefund <= bond`
// (purchased <= allocated is asserted there), so `forfeited` never
// underflows.
export circuit claimRatioBondRefund(
  recipientAddr: Bytes<32>,
  claimedRefund: Uint<128>,
  claimedTreasuryShare: Uint<128>
): [] {
  assert(
    disclose(phase != LaunchPhase.Cancelled && !dvFailed && dvState == DarkVeilState.Closed),
    "Only claimable after a normally-closed, non-cancelled, non-failed DarkVeil"
  );

  const sk = getUserSecret();
  const caller = deriveUserPublicKey(sk);
  assert(disclose(!isKeyZero(caller)), "Invalid user key");
  // Phase 5 hygiene fix: same empty-recipient guard as claimBondRefund above.
  assert(disclose(recipientAddr != pad(32, "")), "Recipient address cannot be empty");

  assert(
    lockedBonds.member(disclose(caller.bytes)),
    "No locked bond found for caller"
  );
  const bond = lockedBonds.lookup(disclose(caller.bytes));
  assert(disclose(bond > 0), "Bond already claimed");

  const purchased = dvTokensPurchased.member(disclose(caller.bytes))
    ? dvTokensPurchased.lookup(disclose(caller.bytes))
    : 0;

  assert(
    disclose(verifyRatioRefund(bond, purchased, baseSlot, claimedRefund)),
    "Claimed refund does not match the ratio-based formula"
  );

  // Clear before paying out (checks-effects-interactions).
  lockedBonds.insert(disclose(caller.bytes), disclose(0));

  const dest = right<ContractAddress, UserAddress>(disclose(UserAddress { bytes: recipientAddr }));
  sendUnshielded(nativeToken(), disclose(claimedRefund), dest);

  // T33: route the forfeited remainder — 60% treasury / 40% ops, matching
  // D5's existing launch-fee-split ratio.
  const forfeited = (bond - claimedRefund) as Uint<128>;
  assert(
    disclose(verifyFeeSlice(forfeited, 6000, claimedTreasuryShare)),
    "Claimed treasury share does not match the 60% split"
  );
  const opsShare = (forfeited - claimedTreasuryShare) as Uint<128>;

  const treasuryDest = right<ContractAddress, UserAddress>(disclose(UserAddress { bytes: treasuryAddr }));
  sendUnshielded(nativeToken(), disclose(claimedTreasuryShare), treasuryDest);
  const opsDest = right<ContractAddress, UserAddress>(disclose(UserAddress { bytes: opsAddr }));
  sendUnshielded(nativeToken(), disclose(opsShare), opsDest);
}

// ============================================================================
// CIRCUITS — BONDING CURVE BUY
// ============================================================================

// Buy tokens from the bonding curve
// The caller provides the expected price (computed off-chain) and we verify it
// via the multiplication invariant (no division needed in circuit)
//
// T-AUDIT finding (2026-07-21, High — documented, not fixed here, needs a
// product/architecture decision): unlike the DarkVeil phase (registration
// and revealBuyCommit both gate on verifyAllowlist, a real ZK-proven
// allowlist Merkle membership check), this PUBLIC phase has NO
// sybil-resistant identity check at all. `caller` below is derived from
// `getUserSecret()`, an entirely unconstrained witness — nothing on-chain
// stops a whale from supplying a fresh secret on every call, resetting
// `priorCumulative` to 0 for each "new identity" and buying past the
// intended 5% walletCap in unlimited increments. This contradicts
// CLAUDE.md's documented claim of "5% cap per ZK identity (strong)" for
// Tier C — the strong-cap guarantee is real for DarkVeil, not for this
// public phase. Closing this for real needs a Sybil-resistance source this
// codebase doesn't currently have for anonymous public buyers (e.g. a
// stake/balance-gated identity proof, or requiring public buyers to also
// clear the same allowlist DarkVeil registrants do) — a design decision,
// not a one-line fix, tracked as an open finding rather than attempted here.
export circuit buyTokens(
  tokenAmount: Uint<128>,
  claimedPrice: Uint<128>,
  grossPayment: Uint<128>,
  claimedCreatorFee: Uint<128>,
  claimedTreasuryFee: Uint<128>,
  claimedOpsFee: Uint<128>,
  timestamp: Uint<64>
): [] {
  // Curve must be active
  assert(disclose(curveState == CurveState.Active), "Bonding curve not active");

  // Verify tokens are still available
  const remaining = (curveSupply - tokensSold) as Uint<128>;
  assert(disclose(tokenAmount > 0), "Must buy positive amount");
  assert(disclose(tokenAmount <= remaining), "Insufficient tokens remaining");

  // Verify the claimed price matches the quadratic bonding curve formula —
  // see verifyPrice for the actual cross-multiplication check.
  assert(
    disclose(verifyPrice(tokensSold, claimedPrice)),
    "Price verification failed"
  );

  // Compute the gross payment (tokenAmount * claimedPrice) and verify it
  // matches what the caller provided.
  assert(disclose(tokenAmount <= 1099511627775), "tokenAmount exceeds safe range"); // 2^40 - 1
  assert(disclose(claimedPrice <= 17592186044415), "claimedPrice exceeds safe range"); // 2^44 - 1
  const expectedGross =
    ((tokenAmount as Uint<40>) as Uint<84>) * ((claimedPrice as Uint<44>) as Uint<84>);
  assert(disclose(grossPayment == (expectedGross as Uint<128>)), "Payment amount mismatch");

  // Verify each claimed fee slice against the fee config's basis points.
  assert(disclose(verifyFeeSlice(grossPayment, feeConfig.creatorBps, claimedCreatorFee)), "Creator fee mismatch");
  assert(disclose(verifyFeeSlice(grossPayment, feeConfig.treasuryBps, claimedTreasuryFee)), "Treasury fee mismatch");
  assert(disclose(verifyFeeSlice(grossPayment, feeConfig.opsBps, claimedOpsFee)), "Ops fee mismatch");

  // T40 fix (2026-07-09): require grossPayment to actually be paid.
  receiveUnshielded(nativeToken(), disclose(grossPayment));

  const feeTotal = ((claimedCreatorFee + claimedTreasuryFee) + claimedOpsFee) as Uint<128>;
  const netPayment = (grossPayment - feeTotal) as Uint<128>;

  creatorFees = disclose((creatorFees + claimedCreatorFee) as Uint<128>);
  treasuryFees = disclose((treasuryFees + claimedTreasuryFee) as Uint<128>);
  opsFees = disclose((opsFees + claimedOpsFee) as Uint<128>);

  tokensSold = disclose((tokensSold + tokenAmount) as Uint<128>);
  totalRaised = disclose((totalRaised + netPayment) as Uint<128>);

  // Derive caller identity — SAME identity used across this whole merged
  // contract now (see file header's identity note).
  const sk = getUserSecret();
  const caller = deriveUserPublicKey(sk);
  assert(disclose(!isKeyZero(caller)), "Invalid user key");
  // T32: creator cannot wash-trade their own public bonding curve (e.g. to
  // force last-mile 100% sell-through and start their own vesting clock).
  assert(disclose(caller.bytes != creatorKey), "Creator cannot buy their own bonding curve");

  // T25 fix (2026-07-10): enforce the 5% cumulative cap atomically, in the
  // same circuit call, against the same cumulativePurchases map DarkVeil
  // registration/checkAndUpdateCap uses — no cross-contract call needed
  // now that this is one contract instead of two. See the file header's
  // "known remaining gap" note: this makes the PUBLIC-phase side of the
  // cap real; DarkVeil-phase purchases still aren't counted here yet.
  const priorCumulative = cumulativePurchases.member(disclose(caller.bytes))
    ? cumulativePurchases.lookup(disclose(caller.bytes))
    : 0;
  const newCumulative = (priorCumulative + tokenAmount) as Uint<128>;
  assert(disclose(newCumulative <= walletCap), "Purchase exceeds 5% wallet cap");
  cumulativePurchases.insert(disclose(caller.bytes), disclose(newCumulative));

  // Credit tokens to buyer's balance
  const currentBal = balances.member(disclose(caller.bytes))
    ? balances.lookup(disclose(caller.bytes))
    : 0;
  const newBal = (currentBal + tokenAmount) as Uint<128>;
  balances.insert(disclose(caller.bytes), disclose(newBal));

  // Track cumulative NIGHT paid too, for claimCurveRefund() if the curve
  // is later cancelled.
  const currentPaid = paidByBuyer.member(disclose(caller.bytes))
    ? paidByBuyer.lookup(disclose(caller.bytes))
    : 0;
  const newPaid = (currentPaid + grossPayment) as Uint<128>;
  paidByBuyer.insert(disclose(caller.bytes), disclose(newPaid));

  // Record the buy
  const recordId = persistentHash<BuyRecordIdInput>(BuyRecordIdInput {
    buyerKey: caller.bytes,
    launchId: launchId,
    amount: tokenAmount,
    timestamp: timestamp
  });
  buyRecords.insert(disclose(recordId), disclose(BuyRecord {
    buyerKey: caller.bytes,
    amount: tokenAmount,
    pricePaid: grossPayment,
    feeCharged: feeTotal,
    timestamp: timestamp
  }));
  buyCount.increment(1);

  // Check graduation: if all tokens sold, graduate
  if (disclose(tokensSold == curveSupply)) {
    curveState = CurveState.Graduated;
  }
}

// ============================================================================
// CIRCUITS — VIEW / READ
// ============================================================================

// T100 fix (2026-07-22): currentPrice() removed rather than fixed in place.
// It always returned basePrice — never referencing tokensSold/maxPrice/
// curveSupply at all — because the real formula
// (price = basePrice + (maxPrice-basePrice) * (tokensSold/curveSupply)^2)
// needs division, which Compact cannot do in-circuit (the same constraint
// verifyPrice's own header documents at length: a division-free
// cross-multiplication check works for VERIFYING a caller-supplied claim,
// but there is no caller-supplied claim here for a zero-argument view
// circuit to verify against). Kept as a stub that lied about its own
// output would be worse than removing it outright. basePrice/maxPrice/
// curveSupply are now `export`ed (see their declarations above) precisely
// so this same formula can be computed correctly off-chain — the same
// division-in-TypeScript pattern Tier A's real `curvePriceAt()` already
// uses for its own (linear, Aiken-side) curve, and the pattern T100's own
// finding recommended.

// Get tokens remaining on the curve
export circuit tokensRemaining(): Uint<128> {
  return (curveSupply - tokensSold) as Uint<128>;
}

// Get buyer's token balance
export circuit balanceOf(buyerKey: Bytes<32>): Uint<128> {
  const bal = balances.member(disclose(buyerKey))
    ? balances.lookup(disclose(buyerKey))
    : 0;
  return disclose(bal);
}

// Get total raised (net of fees)
export circuit totalRaisedNet(): Uint<128> {
  return totalRaised;
}

// Get fee accumulators
export circuit getFees(): FeeConfig {
  return disclose(feeConfig);
}

// ============================================================================
// CIRCUITS — ADMIN / GOVERNOR
// ============================================================================

// Update allowlist root (for late additions)
export circuit updateAllowlistRoot(newRoot: Bytes<32>): [] {
  const govSecret = getGovernorSecret();
  const govKey = deriveGovernorKey(govSecret);
  assert(disclose(govKey == governorKey), "Only governor can update allowlist");
  allowlistRoot = disclose(newRoot);
}

// Record that DarkVeil failed (<50% participation) — T22 resolution.
export circuit markDarkVeilFailed(): [] {
  const govSecret = getGovernorSecret();
  const govKey = deriveGovernorKey(govSecret);
  assert(disclose(govKey == governorKey), "Only governor can mark DarkVeil failed");
  assert(disclose(!dvFailed), "DarkVeil already marked failed");
  dvFailed = disclose(true);
}

// Advance to next phase
export circuit advancePhase(newPhase: LaunchPhase): [] {
  const govSecret = getGovernorSecret();
  const govKey = deriveGovernorKey(govSecret);
  assert(disclose(govKey == governorKey), "Only governor can advance phase");

  if (disclose(newPhase == LaunchPhase.DarkVeil)) {
    assert(disclose(phase == LaunchPhase.Pending), "Must be in Pending to start DarkVeil");
  }
  if (disclose(newPhase == LaunchPhase.Public)) {
    assert(disclose(phase == LaunchPhase.DarkVeil), "Must be in DarkVeil to start Public");
  }
  if (disclose(newPhase == LaunchPhase.Graduated)) {
    assert(disclose(phase == LaunchPhase.Public), "Must be in Public to graduate");
  }
  if (disclose(newPhase == LaunchPhase.Cancelled)) {
    assert(disclose(phase != LaunchPhase.Graduated), "Cannot cancel after graduation");
  }

  phase = disclose(newPhase);
}

// Activate the bonding curve (governor only). Now also gated on `phase`
// being Public — a check that wasn't possible before this merge, since
// `phase` lived in a different contract. Prevents the curve activating
// before DarkVeil has actually closed. `timestamp` is stamped into
// curveActivatedAt for expireCurve (T29) to measure against.
//
// T-AUDIT note (2026-07-21, Low): unlike every other timestamp in this
// file, `timestamp` here is intentionally NOT bound to blockTimeGte/Lte —
// it's governor-only and this plan's own approved test decision (see
// TIER_A_PREPROD_MILESTONE.md's "ExpireCurve testing: backdated
// current_timestamp approved" note) relies on the governor being able to
// pass a deliberately old value for the 90-day-stall test path. Since only
// the trusted governor can call this, a backdated value only ever shortens
// that SAME governor's own curve's runway — never anyone else's — so this
// is an accepted, deliberate exception, not an oversight.
export circuit activateCurve(timestamp: Uint<64>): [] {
  const govSecret = getGovernorSecret();
  const govKey = deriveGovernorKey(govSecret);
  assert(disclose(govKey == governorKey), "Only governor can activate");
  assert(disclose(phase == LaunchPhase.Public), "Must be in Public phase to activate curve");
  assert(disclose(curveState == CurveState.Inactive), "Curve already active");
  curveState = CurveState.Active;
  curveActivatedAt = disclose(timestamp);
}

// Cancel the launch (governor only, for failure path)
export circuit cancelCurve(): [] {
  const govSecret = getGovernorSecret();
  const govKey = deriveGovernorKey(govSecret);
  assert(disclose(govKey == governorKey), "Only governor can cancel");
  assert(disclose(curveState != CurveState.Graduated), "Cannot cancel after graduation");
  curveState = CurveState.Cancelled;
}

// Permissionless force-cancel once the curve has been Active for longer
// than 90 days (7_776_000 seconds — same T29 default as the Cardano Aiken
// bonding curves) without reaching Graduated. No governor signature
// required; the deadline check itself is the authorization, same trust
// model as this file's own closeDarkVeil-adjacent timeouts. Once
// Cancelled, buyers can already recover their NIGHT via claimCurveRefund
// (unlike Tier A/B's atomic-delivery model, Tier C's balances are internal
// ledger credits, not delivered tokens, so a real refund path already
// existed here — this circuit just makes it reachable without depending
// on the governor acting).
// Design requirement: `timestamp` is never a bare caller-
// supplied parameter compared directly against the deadline, so any caller
// could pass an arbitrarily large value and force-cancel any Active curve
// immediately. Now checked against real chain time via blockTimeGt, which
// cannot be satisfied until that much wall-clock time has actually passed.
export circuit expireCurve(): [] {
  assert(disclose(curveState == CurveState.Active), "Curve not active");
  assert(
    blockTimeGt((curveActivatedAt + 7776000) as Uint<64>),
    "Curve has not yet exceeded max duration"
  );
  curveState = CurveState.Cancelled;
}

// Claim a refund of NIGHT paid, after the curve is cancelled (T29 failure
// path). NIGHT is a real Midnight-native unshielded token, so
// sendUnshielded pays it back directly — no cross-chain step needed.
export circuit claimCurveRefund(recipientAddr: Bytes<32>): [] {
  assert(disclose(curveState == CurveState.Cancelled), "Curve not cancelled");

  const sk = getUserSecret();
  const caller = deriveUserPublicKey(sk);
  // Phase 5 hygiene fix: same empty-recipient guard as claimBondRefund.
  assert(disclose(recipientAddr != pad(32, "")), "Recipient address cannot be empty");

  assert(
    paidByBuyer.member(disclose(caller.bytes)),
    "No payment found for caller"
  );
  const paid = paidByBuyer.lookup(disclose(caller.bytes));
  assert(disclose(paid > 0), "Refund already claimed");

  paidByBuyer.insert(disclose(caller.bytes), disclose(0));

  const dest = right<ContractAddress, UserAddress>(disclose(UserAddress { bytes: recipientAddr }));
  sendUnshielded(nativeToken(), disclose(paid), dest);
}

// Withdraw accumulated fees (governor only, routes to appropriate wallets)
// Design requirement: this must never only decrement the three
// counters below with a comment deferring to "the Zswap layer via
// transaction merging" — a mechanism that doesn't exist (see witnesses.ts).
// Every graduated Tier C launch's fees were permanently unrecoverable.
// Now pays out for real via sendUnshielded, same pattern claimBondRefund/
// claimRatioBondRefund already use, to the three fixed addresses pinned at
// deploy (creatorAddr/treasuryAddr/opsAddr) so the governor can route
// amounts but never redirect the destination.
export circuit withdrawFees(
  creatorAmount: Uint<128>,
  treasuryAmount: Uint<128>,
  opsAmount: Uint<128>
): [] {
  const govSecret = getGovernorSecret();
  const govKey = deriveGovernorKey(govSecret);
  assert(disclose(govKey == governorKey), "Only governor can withdraw");

  // Security-audit fix (Phase 2): withdrawFees previously had no
  // curveState guard at all. claimCurveRefund pays a cancelled curve's
  // buyers back their FULL gross payment (fee-inclusive) once
  // curveState == Cancelled, but withdrawFees could still separately
  // withdraw those same fees against the same underlying NIGHT balance —
  // whichever party's sendUnshielded landed first would succeed, turning
  // buyer refunds into a race against governor fee withdrawal. Fees on a
  // cancelled/failed launch are void, consistent with buyers getting
  // their gross payment back in full.
  assert(disclose(curveState != CurveState.Cancelled), "Cannot withdraw fees from a cancelled curve");

  assert(disclose(creatorAmount <= creatorFees), "Insufficient creator fees");
  assert(disclose(treasuryAmount <= treasuryFees), "Insufficient treasury fees");
  assert(disclose(opsAmount <= opsFees), "Insufficient ops fees");

  creatorFees = disclose(creatorFees - creatorAmount);
  treasuryFees = disclose(treasuryFees - treasuryAmount);
  opsFees = disclose(opsFees - opsAmount);

  // CTO fee-redirect fix (2026-07-12): the creator's share now goes to
  // communityWallet once a CTO has been triggered, same
  // active_fee_recipient pattern as the Cardano curve contracts (Tier A/B)
  // and lp_escrow.ak's T13. treasuryAddr/opsAddr are unaffected by CTO —
  // only the CREATOR's income stream redirects (CLAUDE.md's "What a Passed
  // Vote Does" #1: "Creator fee escrow future payments -> CTO wallet").
  const creatorRecipient = disclose(ctoTriggered) ? communityWallet : creatorAddr;
  const creatorDest = right<ContractAddress, UserAddress>(disclose(UserAddress { bytes: creatorRecipient }));
  sendUnshielded(nativeToken(), disclose(creatorAmount), creatorDest);
  const treasuryDest = right<ContractAddress, UserAddress>(disclose(UserAddress { bytes: treasuryAddr }));
  sendUnshielded(nativeToken(), disclose(treasuryAmount), treasuryDest);
  const opsDest = right<ContractAddress, UserAddress>(disclose(UserAddress { bytes: opsAddr }));
  sendUnshielded(nativeToken(), disclose(opsAmount), opsDest);
}

// Trigger CTO — governor only, called after a SilenceLockTrigger proposal
// passes on cto_governance.compact (separate transaction — no
// cross-contract call mechanism exists in Compact, T2/T25). Redirects
// withdrawFees' creator share to communityWallet. Same pattern as
// lp_escrow.compact/creator_escrow.compact's own triggerCTO.
export circuit triggerCTO(communityWalletAddr: Bytes<32>): [] {
  const govSecret = getGovernorSecret();
  const govKey = deriveGovernorKey(govSecret);
  assert(disclose(govKey == governorKey), "Only governor can trigger CTO");
  assert(disclose(!ctoTriggered), "CTO already triggered");
  // Phase 5 hygiene fix (2026-07-12): an empty communityWalletAddr would
  // silently make every future creator-fee claim un-routable (redirected to
  // a zero address) once CTO triggers — larger blast radius than a single
  // claimant's own refund, so worth guarding here too.
  assert(disclose(communityWalletAddr != pad(32, "")), "Community wallet address cannot be empty");
  ctoTriggered = disclose(true);
  communityWallet = disclose(communityWalletAddr);
}

// Dissolve CTO — governor only, called after a DissolveCTO proposal passes
// (creator returned). Reverts withdrawFees' creator share back to
// creatorAddr.
export circuit dissolveCTO(): [] {
  const govSecret = getGovernorSecret();
  const govKey = deriveGovernorKey(govSecret);
  assert(disclose(govKey == governorKey), "Only governor can dissolve CTO");
  assert(disclose(ctoTriggered), "CTO not triggered");
  ctoTriggered = disclose(false);
  communityWallet = disclose(pad(32, ""));
}

// Move net raised proceeds into the LP escrow once the curve has
// graduated. Design requirement: graduation previously only
// flipped curveState — no circuit ever moved totalRaised anywhere, so a
// graduated launch's entire raise had no way out of this contract.
// Permissionless — same "the condition is the authorization" idiom as
// expireCurve/Graduate elsewhere, since lpSeeded prevents replay and the
// destination (lpEscrowAddr) is fixed at deploy, not caller-supplied.
export circuit graduateLp(): [] {
  assert(disclose(curveState == CurveState.Graduated), "Curve has not graduated");
  assert(disclose(!lpSeeded), "LP already seeded");
  lpSeeded = disclose(true);

  const dest = right<ContractAddress, UserAddress>(disclose(UserAddress { bytes: lpEscrowAddr }));
  sendUnshielded(nativeToken(), disclose(totalRaised), dest);
}

// ============================================================================
// PRIVACY ANALYSIS
// ============================================================================
//
// What goes ON-CHAIN (public ledger):
//   - launchId, allowlistRoot, phase, totalSupply, maxWalletPercent,
//     bondAmount, walletCap, basePrice, maxPrice, curveSupply, dvAllocation,
//     dvPrice, allowlistSize, registrationCloseTime (sealed)
//   - curveState, tokensSold, totalRaised (public for transparency)
//   - dvState, totalTokensCommitted, totalRaisedCommitted (public for
//     transparency — aggregates only, individual amounts stay hidden until
//     each buyer's own revealBuyCommit call, see below)
//   - creatorFees, treasuryFees, opsFees (public for transparency)
//   - ctoTriggered, communityWallet (public — CTO fee-redirect fix, T51.
//     communityWallet is only ever meaningful once ctoTriggered is true;
//     pad(32,"") beforehand)
//   - cumulativePurchases, balances, lockedBonds, paidByBuyer (keyed by
//     UserPublicKey, not real identity)
//   - buyRecords (keyed by record hash, contains UserPublicKey)
//   - commitments (commitment hashes + nullifiers — not linkable to
//     identity until revealed; a revealed commitment's amount is public,
//     but WHICH UserPublicKey it belongs to is still just a hash)
//   - registrationNullifiers, buyNullifiers (commitment hashes, not
//     linkable to identity)
//   - registrationCount, buyCount, dvTotalParticipants (aggregate counters)
//   - fairLaunchCert (public certificate, generated on DarkVeil close)
//   - feeConfig (public, for transparency)
//   - governorKey (derived, not raw secret)
//
// What stays PRIVATE (never leaves the prover):
//   - User's secret key (getUserSecret witness)
//   - Merkle proof (getMerkleProof witness) — the allowlist leaf itself is
//     no longer a free witness (design requirement): it's derived in-circuit from
//     the caller's own identity, so there's no separate leaf value to keep
//     private beyond the identity itself
//   - Registration nonce (getRegistrationNonce witness)
//   - DarkVeil buy nonce (getBuyNonce witness)
//   - Governor's secret key (getGovernorSecret witness)
//   - A DarkVeil buyer's purchase amount, BETWEEN submitBuyCommit and their
//     own revealBuyCommit call — the commitment hash hides it; nothing
//     about the amount is ever disclosed until the buyer themself reveals
//
// Privacy notes:
//   - Allowlist membership is proven via ZK without revealing which entry
//   - Buy amounts and prices are PUBLIC on the bonding curve's public phase
//     (by design). DarkVeil buy amounts are private UNTIL each buyer's own
//     reveal — the commit/reveal split is what makes DarkVeil "private": a
//     buyer's amount is hidden for the whole Buying phase, only becoming
//     public at the SAME moment payment is verified (T25 follow-up,
//     2026-07-10 — deliberately not checked earlier, to avoid disclosing
//     the amount to receiveUnshielded's argument before the feature itself
//     was ever going to make it public anyway)
//   - UserPublicKey is a domain-separated hash of the user's secret — not
//     linkable to their real-world identity or to other launches. ONE
//     domain now for the whole merged contract (see file header's identity
//     note) — deliberate, not a privacy loosening: cumulativePurchases was
//     always meant to link one identity's activity across DarkVeil and the
//     public phase, so a single consistent identity is what the feature
//     requires, not an accidental correlation
//   - Registration/buy nullifiers are unique per (user, launch[, nonce]) —
//     prevent double-registration/double-buying without revealing which
//     user registered or bought
//   - Cumulative purchases/balances are visible by UserPublicKey, but the
//     mapping from UserPublicKey to real identity is unknown
//
// ============================================================================
